The error is in the `sorry` part. We need to prove:
`⊢ (b, @S b) ∈ Error.resultSet n a S ⟨σ, Error.resultSet._proof_2 n σ a c o⟩ ∨ (b, @S b) ∈ Error.resultSet n c S ⟨σ, Error.resultSet._proof_2 n σ a c o⟩`

We have:
- `this : @S b = true` (so `b` is true)
- `a_knows_after_t : Error.eval n S ⟨Error.Call.normal n a c :: σ, o⟩ (Error.Form.K n a (Error.Form.Has n b (b, true)))`
- `ra : roleOfIn a C = Other`

From `a_knows_after_t`, we can use `not_in_call_then_invariant_kv` to conclude that `a` knows `b` in the original sequence `σ`.
`not_in_call_then_invariant_kv` states:
`eval S ⟨C :: σ,  o⟩ (Kv a b) ↔ eval S ⟨     σ, ⁻o⟩ (Kv a b)`
Since `a_knows_after_t` means `eval S ⟨Error.Call.normal n a c :: σ, o⟩ (Kv a b)` is true, the right side must also be true.
So, `eval S ⟨σ, ⁻o⟩ (Kv a b)` is true.
This means `a` knows `b` in the sequence `σ`.
By definition of `resultSet`, this means `b ∈ S⌈σ⌉a`.
This proves the left side of the disjunction.

