The goal is to prove:
`⊢ (b, @S b) ∈ Error.resultSet n a S ⟨σ, Error.resultSet._proof_2 n σ a c o⟩ ∨ (b, @S b) ∈ Error.resultSet n c S ⟨σ, Error.resultSet._proof_2 n σ a c o⟩`

We have:
- `this : @S b = true`
- `a_not_know_before_t : ¬Error.eval n S ⟨σ, Error.Sequence.maxOne_cons n (Error.Call.normal n a c) σ o⟩ (Error.Form.K n a (Error.Form.Has n b (b, true)))`
- `a_not_know_before_f : ¬Error.eval n S ⟨σ, Error.Sequence.maxOne_cons n (Error.Call.normal n a c) σ o⟩ (Error.Form.K n a (Error.Form.Has n b (b, false)))`
- `a_knows_after_t : Error.eval n S ⟨Error.Call.normal n a c :: σ, o⟩ (Error.Form.K n a (Error.Form.Has n b (b, true)))`

Let's think. `a_knows_after_t` means that after the call `C = Error.Call.normal n a c`, agent `a` knows `Has n b (b, true)`. `Has n b (b, true)` is equivalent to `(b, true)`. So `a` knows `(b, true)`. What does it mean for `a` to know `(b, true)`? It means that `(b, true)` is in `a`'s result set.

So `(b, @S b) ∈ Error.resultSet n a S ⟨σ, ...⟩`. Therefore the left side of the disjunction is true. The whole disjunction is true.

So we can prove the goal by showing that `(b, @S b) ∈ Error.resultSet n a S ⟨σ, ...⟩`.

