```lean
import Mathlib


/-!
This is a formalization of parts of the paper "Can We Trust the Cloud? A Formal Analysis of the Knowledge and Beliefs of Agents in a Distributed System" by A. D. Kerber and S. A. Smolka.

The main parts formalized are:
- The definition of the system and the basic properties of knowledge and belief
- Lemma 7: If two processes are indistinguishable to an agent, then they must have the same values for the agent
- Lemma 8: The truth value of any $b_a$ atom is known by agent $a$
- Lemma 9: Knowledge of secrets is preserved
- Lemma 10: Agents know their own value
- Lemma 11: If an agent knows the value of a proposition, then the proposition must be true in the actual state

The proof uses the following key concepts:
- `OSequence`: A sequence of operations in the system
- `Agent`: A participant in the system
- `Call`: An atomic operation in the system
- `Dist`: A distribution of values in the system
- `Kv`: Knowledge of a value
- `eval`: The evaluation of a term in the system
- `resultSet`: The set of results known to an agent
- `equiv`: Equivalence between two sequences or distributions
- `stubbornness`: A property of the system ensuring consistency
- `indistinguishable`: A relation between two sequences or distributions
- `local_is_known`: A property ensuring local knowledge
- `knowledge_of_secrets_is_preserved`: A property ensuring preservation of knowledge
- `know_your_own`: A property ensuring self-knowledge
- `not_in_call_then_invariant`: A property ensuring invariance outside calls

The proof relies heavily on induction on the sequence of operations and case analysis on the role of the agent in each operation.
-/
